\begin_layout Part
Cancer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Causes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Checkpoints and formation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mitosis system evolved to have checkpoints in place:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
nucleolus not divided
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
sufficient skin growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different rates for cells, the cell cycle is highly controlled:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
skin -> high
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
neurons -> low
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
red blood doesnt ever
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cancer is the uncontrolled and rapid division of cells.
 The mass of cancer cells forms tumors.
 The rapid and unchecked division of cells leads to further mutation which
 can cause cells to leave their primary sites and form satellite tumors
 in a process called metastasis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cancer Genetics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mutations which take place on genes that control cell division directly
 are called Oncogenes and lead to uncontrolled proliferation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are also genes that act as tumor suppressors, these are often recessive
 and both copies of the genes need to be effected in order to cause the
 uncontrolled proliferation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Example: Gene p53
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gene which codes for a protein that acts as a transcriptionial regulator
 that attaches DNA and turns genes on.
 It plays roles in tumor suppression, DNA damage repair, triggers cell division
 and initiating cell growth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amino acids located at the center of the p53 protein controls its ability
 to regulate transcription of genes necessary for either cell division or
 cell death according to the organsiams needs.
 It is mutations of the gene of the p53 protein here which eventually lead
 to cancer formations via uncontrolled transcription genes controlling cell
 proliferation.
 
\end_layout

